   <div class=\"partner-logo-alignment\">\n                <!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The American Astronomical Society (AAS), established in 1899 and based in Washington, DC, is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America. Its membership of about 7,000 individuals also includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers, and others whose research and educational interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects comprising contemporary astronomy. The mission of the AAS is to enhance and share humanity's scientific understanding of the universe.</p> <p><a href=\"https://aas.org/\">https://aas.org/</a></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n</a>\n<span class=\"overlay-set\">\n    <div class=\"tint-screen\"></div>\n    <div class=\"overlay-panel\">\n        <a title=\"Close\"  class=\"close-icon close-overlay\" tabindex=\"0\" role=\"button\" aria-describedby=\"close-icon-description\"><span class=\"icon-close\"></span></a>\n        <p id=\"close-icon-description\" class=\"offscreen-hidden\">Click here to close this overlay, or press the \"Escape\" key on your keyboard.</p>\n        <div class=\"overlay-img\">\n            <a href=\"\">\n                <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n            </a>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The Institute of Physics (IOP) is a leading scientific society promoting physics and bringing physicists together for the benefit of all. It has a worldwide membership of around 50 000 comprising physicists from all sectors, as well as those with an interest in physics. It works to advance physics research, application and education; and engages with policy makers and the public to develop awareness and understanding of physics. Its publishing company, IOP Publishing, is a world leader in professional scientific communications.</p> <p><a href=\"https://www.iop.org\">https://www.iop.org</a></p></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<p></p>\n                </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n<!-- Branded journal header ends -->\n</div> <!-- end secondary-header -->\n<!-- Secondary header ends --><div class=\"da1-da2\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ScholarlyArticle\" id=\"page-content\">\n            <div class=\"da1 ta1 article-head\">\n                <!-- Start Eyebrow block, containing Surtitle and Labels -->\n<div class=\"eyebrow\">\n\t<!-- Start Collection Labels -->\n    <!-- End Collection Labels --> </div>\n<!-- End Eyebrow block -->\n\n<h1 itemprop=\"headline\" class=\"wd-jnl-art-title\">Survey of Gravitationally Lensed Objects in HSC Imaging (SuGOHI). You will need to select a minimum of one corridor.\n                    </p>\n                </div>\n                <div class=\"overlay-panel__container\">\n                    <div class=\"overlay-panel__col\">\n                        <fieldset id=\"alerts-corridors-list\">\n                            <legend id=\"corridors-title\" class=\"overlay-panel__heading replica-h3 mb-05\">Corridors</legend>\n                        </fieldset>\n                    </div>\n                    <div class=\"overlay-panel__col\">\n                        <fieldset id=\"alerts-journals-list\">\n                            <legend id=\"journals-title\" class=\"overlay-panel__heading replica-h3 mb-05\">Journals</legend>\n                        </fieldset>\n                    </div>\n                    <div class=\"boxout-bg-blue-light overlay-panel__extra-info\">\n                        <p>\n                            Please note, The Astrophysical Journal Letters (ApJL) and Research Notes of the AAS (RNAAS)\n                            do not currently use the corridors.\n                        </p>\n                    </div>\n                </div>\n                <div class=\"overlay-panel__footer\">\n                    <div class=\"overlay-panel__inner-footer\">\n                        <input id=\"update-alerts\" type=\"submit\" value=\"Create alert\" class=\"btn btn-default overlay-panel__btn\" role=\"button\">\n                        <div class=\"icon-spinner spinner overlay-panel__loading\"></div>\n                    </div>\n                </div>\n            </form>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- End TOC Subjects Popup -->\n            <p class=\"mb-0\"><a class=\"wd-jnl-email-alert jnl-email-alert--corridors-info\" href=\"https://journals.aas.org/corridors.html\"\n               target=\"_blank\" title=\"Find out more about AAS corridors.\">\n                What are corridors? <span class=\"icon-newtab\">\n            </a></p>\n        </div>\n\n    <!-- End Email Alert -->\n<!-- End Email Alert --><!-- Start Citation Alert Link -->\n                        <p>\n<div class=\"jnl-notifications-wrapper\">\n    <a class=\"wd-jnl-email-alert\" href=\"https://myiopscience.iop.org/signin?origin=a0&return=https%3A%2F%2Fiopscience.iop.org%2Fmyiopscience%2Falerts%2Fsubscribe%3FarticleID%3D0004-637X%2F867%2F2%2F107\"><span\n            class=\"icon-alarm icon-alarm--jhp\"></span>Create citation alert</a>\n</div><!-- End Citation Alert Link -->\n                    </div>\n\t\t</div>\n    </div>\n    <!-- Article information ends -->\n<!-- Start Info top-->\n    <!-- end Info top --><div class=\"article-content\">\n\t<span id=\"articleId\" class=\"hide\">0004-637X/867/2/107</span>\n<!-- Start Abstract -->\n    <h2 id=\"artAbst\" class=\"collapse-blocked\">Abstract</h2>\n        <!-- Start article video abstract -->\n\t<!-- End article video abstract -->\n\t<div class=\"article-text wd-jnl-art-abstract cf\" itemprop=\"description\">\n             <P>We investigate the local and line-of-sight (LOS) overdensities of strong gravitational lens galaxies using wide-area multiband imaging from the Hyper Suprime-Cam Subaru Strategic Program. We present 41\u00a0new definite or probable lens candidates discovered in Data Release 2 of the survey. Using a combined sample of 87\u00a0galaxy-scale lenses out to a lens redshift of <I>z</I> <SUB>L</SUB>\u00a0~\u00a00.8, we compare galaxy number counts in LOSs toward known and newly discovered lenses in the survey to those of a control sample consisting of random LOSs. We also compare the local overdensity of lens galaxies to a sample of \"twin\" galaxies that have similar redshift and velocity dispersion to test whether lenses lie in different environments from similar nonlens galaxies. We find that lens fields contain higher number counts of galaxies compared to the control fields, but this effect arises from the local environment of the lens. Once galaxies in the lens plane are removed, the lens LOSs are consistent with the control sample. The local environments of the lenses are overdense compared to the control sample, and are slightly overdense compared to those of the twin sample, although the significance is marginal. There is no significant evidence of the evolution of the local overdensity of lens environments with redshift.</P> </div>\n    <!-- End abstract -->\n<!-- Start Export citation and abstract tools -->\n\t<p>\n\t\t<small>Export citation and abstract</small>\n\t\t<span class=\"btn-multi-block\">\n\t\t\t<a href=\"/export?articleId=0004-637X/867/2/107&doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381&exportFormat=iopexport_bib&exportType=abs&navsubmit=Export+abstract\" class=\"btn btn-primary wd-btn-cit-abs-bib\" title=\"Export BibTex\">BibTeX</a>\n\t\t\t<a href=\"/export?articleId=0004-637X/867/2/107&doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381&exportFormat=iopexport_ris&exportType=abs&navsubmit=Export+abstract\" class=\"btn btn-primary wd-btn-cit-abs-ris\" title=\"Export RIS\">RIS</a>\n\t\t</span>\n\t</p>\n<!-- End Export citation and abstract tools -->\n<!-- Start AAS Related Links -->\n<div class=\"reveal-container reveal-closed reveal-plus-icon bdt-1 mt-2 mb-2 wd-jnl-art-article-aas-related-links\">\n  <div class=\"replica-h3 mt-0\">\n    <a href=\"#\" class=\"reveal-trigger\" data-reveal-label-alt=\"Hide related links\">Related links</a>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"reveal-content\">\n    <div class=\"article-meta\"> \n      <ul>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...867..107W\" target=\"_blank\">NASA ADS Record <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?refcode=2018ApJ...867..107W&search_type=Search \" target=\"_blank\">NED Objects <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"/journal/0004-637X/page/About%20Related%20Links\" target=\"_blank\">About Related Links</a></li>\n      \t</ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<!-- Start info bottom -->\n    <!-- End info bottom -->\n<!-- Start article full text -->\n\t<div xmlns:book=\"http://api.iop.org/Book/1.0/\" itemprop=\"articleBody\" class=\"wd-jnl-art-full-text article-text\">\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s1\" name=\"apjaae381s1\">1.\u00a0Introduction</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Strong gravitational lensing is a useful tool for studying the distribution of matter in the universe. The lensing effect arises from the total mass distribution along the line of sight (LOS)\u2014including both baryonic and dark matter\u2014and is generally dominated by the primary lensing mass. Thus, lensing is a unique probe of the mass structure of lens galaxies (e.g., Treu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib74\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib74\">2006</a>; Koopmans et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib46\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib46\">2009</a>; Auger et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib6\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib6\">2010</a>; Sonnenfeld et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib68\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib68\">2013b</a>). Strongly lensed quasars can also be used to probe the Hubble constant (<em>H</em><sub>0</sub>) through a measurement of their time delays (Refsdal <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib59\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib59\">1964</a>), independent of and complementary to other probes such as the cosmological distance ladder (e.g., Freedman et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib32\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib32\">2012</a>; Riess et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib60\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib60\">2016</a>). The latest constraints from time-delay lenses (Bonvin et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib11\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib11\">2017</a>; Suyu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib69\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib69\">2017</a>; Wong et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib79\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib79\">2017b</a>) show a higher <em>H</em><sub>0</sub> value than <em>Planck</em> CMB measurements, highlighting the importance of this independent probe.</p><p>However, lenses do not exist in isolation, but are embedded within the large-scale structure of the universe, including both the local lens environment and uncorrelated structure in projection. The lensing signal is perturbed by the integrated effect of the LOS mass distribution from the observer back to the source redshift, <em>z</em><sub>S</sub>. Most of these perturbations are small and can be either ignored or approximated as a tidal perturbation (see McCully et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib48\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib48\">2017</a>), but the presence of significant perturbers such as groups and clusters (e.g., Momcheva et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib52\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib52\">2006</a>; Wong et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib78\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib78\">2011</a>; Wilson et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib75\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib75\">2016</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib76\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib76\">2017</a>; Sluse et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib65\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib65\">2017</a>) or the combined effect of multiple perturbers can lead to biases in lens modeling if unaccounted for.</p><p>If strong lenses are randomly distributed on the sky, these effects should average out over a sufficiently large sample. On the other hand, these LOS structures could potentially boost the lensing efficiency and cause lenses to lie along biased LOSs (e.g., Oguri et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib58\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib58\">2005</a>). In addition, the mass surface density of perturbers along the LOS, which we refer to as external convergence (<em>\u03ba</em><sub>ext</sub>), is unconstrained from lens modeling due to the mass-sheet degeneracy (e.g., Falco et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib27\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib27\">1985</a>; Gorenstein et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib34\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib34\">1988</a>; Saha <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib62\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib62\">2000</a>; Schneider &amp; Sluse <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib63\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib63\">2013</a>; Xu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib80\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib80\">2016</a>). <em>\u03ba</em><sub>ext</sub> does not average out, but instead leads to a bias on the inferred <em>H</em><sub>0</sub> from time-delay lensed quasars if unaccounted for (e.g., Collett et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib18\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib18\">2013</a>; Greene et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib35\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib35\">2013</a>; McCully et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib47\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib47\">2014</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib48\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib48\">2017</a>).</p><p>In order to use strong lens galaxies to infer the generic properties of typical galaxies, it is necessary to ascertain whether or not lenses are in unbiased LOSs and have environments that are representative of the underlying galaxy population. The Sloan Lens ACS Survey (SLACS; Bolton et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib9\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib9\">2006</a>) studied over 100 galaxy-scale strong lenses and found that their structural properties are consistent with that of similar early-type nonlens galaxies (Bolton et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib10\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib10\">2008</a>) and reside in similar local environments (Treu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>). However, the SLACS sample is primarily at low redshift (<em>z</em><sub>L</sub> ~ 0.2) and is selected through spectroscopic identification of background sources. It is not known whether this holds true for lenses selected by broadband imaging at higher redshifts, where the clustering and bias properties of galaxies may differ from those selected by SLACS.</p><p>Using <em>Hubble Space Telescope</em> (<em>HST</em>) imaging, Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>) studied the LOSs toward 20 known strong-lens galaxies, using galaxy number counts to evaluate the LOS overdensity relative to a control sample of randomly chosen LOSs. This study found that the LOS toward lenses tends to be overdense, but much of this effect arises from the local environment of the lens galaxies, which are biased toward massive elliptical galaxies and are known to cluster (e.g., Dressler <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib23\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib23\">1980</a>). Once the local lens environment is corrected for, the relative densities of the lens LOS are not significantly different from the random sample, which is consistent with results from cosmological simulations (Hilbert et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib36\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib36\">2007</a>). However, this study had several limitations, including the small sample size of lenses and the relatively small field of view of the <em>HST</em> Advanced Camera for Surveys, which only allowed for a maximum aperture radius of 45'' over which to evaluate the LOS. In addition, there were uncertainties arising from cosmic variance due to a small control sample of truly random fields, as a larger contiguous control field was itself found to be biased. Furthermore, this study lacked galaxy redshifts to distinguish the contribution of the local lens environment from projected structure along the LOS, instead relying on a statistical correction based on galaxy clustering results.</p><p>Using deep multiband imaging data from the ongoing Hyper Suprime Cam Subaru Strategic Program (HSC SSP; Aihara et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib4\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib4\">2018b</a>), we have recently discovered dozens of new gravitational lenses as part of the Survey of Gravitationally lensed Objects in HSC Imaging (SuGOHI; Sonnenfeld et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib66\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib66\">2018</a>) project. With the sample of SuGOHI galaxy-scale lenses (hereafter \"SuGOHI-g\"), we use the high-quality imaging from the HSC SSP to overcome the technical limitations of the Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>) analysis and study LOSs toward strong lenses in much more detail than has been possible in the past. The deep multiband imaging provides accurate photometric redshifts (Tanaka et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib71\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib71\">2018</a>) for distinguishing galaxies in the local lens environment from those projected along the LOS. In addition, the SuGOHI-g sample includes lenses up to <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a00.8, allowing us to study lens environments to higher redshifts than was previously possible with the SLACS sample, and to compare them to nonlens galaxies of similar redshift and mass. Finally, detailed analyses of individual SuGOHI-g lenses may require ancillary data, and it will be useful to consider which lenses are likely to be impacted by overdense environments or LOSs when deciding which systems to prioritize for such follow-up observations.</p><p>This paper is organized as follows. We describe the HSC SSP imaging data and BOSS spectroscopic data used in this study in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s2\">2</a>. In Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s3\">3</a>, we present newly discovered lens candidates in Data Release 2 of the HSC SSP. We describe our sample selection of lenses for this study, as well as our selection of twin galaxies and control fields in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s4\">4</a>. In Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s5\">5</a>, we describe our methodology for calculating the density of the local environment and the LOS. We present our main results in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s6\">6</a> and summarize our conclusions in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s7\">7</a>. Throughout this paper, we assume \u03a9<sub><em>m</em></sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.3, \u03a9<sub>\u039b</sub>\u00a0=0.7, and <em>h</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.7. All magnitudes given are on the AB system.</p></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s2\" name=\"apjaae381s2\">2.\u00a0Data</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjaae381s2-1\" name=\"apjaae381s2-1\">2.1.\u00a0Hyper Suprime-Cam Imaging Data</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The HSC SSP (Aihara et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib4\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib4\">2018b</a>) is an ongoing imaging survey with the Hyper Suprime-Cam (HSC; Miyazaki et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib51\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib51\">2012</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib50\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib50\">2018</a>; Furusawa et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib33\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib33\">2018</a>; Kawanomoto et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib42\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib42\">2018</a>; Komiyama et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib45\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib45\">2018</a>) on the Subaru Telescope. The Wide component of the HSC SSP will observe a ~1400 deg<sup>2</sup> area in the <em>grizy</em> bands to a depth of <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a026.2. The data used in this study are taken from Data Release 2 of the HSC SSP, which comprises data taken through the S17A semester and covers 776 deg<sup>2</sup> in all bands, including 289 deg<sup>2</sup> to the full depth. The median <em>i</em>-band seeing of the data is ~0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcs.gif\" alt=\"farcs\" align=\"bottom\" />6. The data are reduced with <tt>hscPipe</tt> version 5.4.0 (Bosch et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib12\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib12\">2018</a>), which is based on the Large Synoptic Survey Telescope (LSST) pipeline (Axelrod et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib8\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib8\">2010</a>; Juri\u0107 et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib41\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib41\">2017</a>).</p><p>The photometric redshifts used in this analysis are determined using the <span class=\"small-caps\">mizuki</span> algorithm (Tanaka <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib70\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib70\">2015</a>). A description of its application to the HSC SSP data is presented in Tanaka et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib71\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib71\">2018</a>). The robustness of the photometric redshifts is a function of galaxy redshift and brightness, and is quantified in terms of \u0394<em>z</em>/(1 + <em>z</em><sub>ref</sub>), where <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn1.gif\" alt=\"${\\rm{\\Delta }}z\\equiv | z-{z}_{\\mathrm{ref}}| $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{\\rm{\\Delta }}z\\equiv | z-{z}_{\\mathrm{ref}}|</script></span></span> and <em>z</em><sub>ref</sub> is a reference redshift. The galaxies that we use to quantify the environment and LOS effects are brighter than <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024. Roughly 97% of these galaxies have a photometric redshift of <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a02, which is approximately the median source redshift expected for lenses discovered in similar imaging surveys (Collett <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib16\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib16\">2015</a>). For HSC SSP galaxies that are brighter than <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 and that are assigned a photometric redshift <em>z</em><sub>phot</sub>\u00a0\u2264\u00a02, <span class=\"small-caps\">mizuki</span> has a photometric redshift scatter of <em>\u03c3</em><sub>conv</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.047 and a catastrophic outlier rate (defined as the fraction of objects such that \u0394<em>z</em>/(1 + <em>z</em><sub>true</sub>)\u00a0&gt;\u00a00.15) of 9.0%.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s2-2\" name=\"apjaae381s2-2\">2.2.\u00a0BOSS Spectroscopic Data</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Our sample of strong lenses using various search algorithms (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s4-1\">4.1</a>) is based on a pre-selection of candidate lens galaxies. These candidates are taken from the Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey (BOSS; Dawson et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib22\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib22\">2013</a>), a component of the Sloan Digital Sky Survey III (SDSS-III; Eisenstein et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib26\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib26\">2011</a>). The BOSS sample consists of the LOWZ subsample (primarily <em>z</em> &lt; 0.4 LRGs) and the CMASS subsample (primarily 0.4 &lt; <em>z</em> &lt; 0.7 LRGs). The initial sample of SuGOHI-g lenses used the BOSS Data Release 12 (Alam et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib5\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib5\">2015</a>). The lens galaxy velocity dispersions used in this study come from Data Release 14 (Abolfathi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib2\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib2\">2018</a>).</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s3\" name=\"apjaae381s3\">3.\u00a0New Lens Candidates in Data Release 2 of the HSC SSP</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>The SuGOHI-g sample of lenses are found through a combination of several lens search methodologies, which are described in Sonnenfeld et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib66\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib66\">2018</a>). The primary search method is the <span class=\"small-caps\">YattaLens</span> algorithm, which searches for arc-like features around massive galaxies and fits simple lens models to evaluate the likelihood of those systems being lenses. The new lens candidates discovered in Data Release 2 of the HSC SSP and presented here are found with <span class=\"small-caps\">YattaLens</span>.</p><p>We run <span class=\"small-caps\">YattaLens</span> on 31,286 massive galaxies in BOSS and find 772 lens candidates, 131 of which are in the LOWZ subsample and 641 of which are in the CMASS subsample. These candidates are visually inspected by the coauthors and individually graded using the following scheme:</p><ul class=\"clear-list wd-inline-list\"><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">1.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">Grade A: definite lenses.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">2.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">Grade B: probable lenses.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">3.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">Grade C: possible lenses.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">4.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\">Grade D: nonlenses.</div></li></ul><p>\n</p><p>In total, we find 7 new lenses with an average grade of A, 34 with an average grade of B, and 159 with an average grade of C. The full list of candidates, including grade C systems, can be found online.<sup xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"fnref\"><a class=\"fnref\" href=\"#apjaae381fn1\">16</a></sup>\n We present newly discovered lenses with an average grade of A or B in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t1\">1</a>. We show images of the grade A lenses in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f1\">1</a> and the grade B lens candidates in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f2\">2</a>. The BOSS spectra are visually inspected to identify emission lines from the lensed source, and thus measure the source redshift. However, we are only able to measure the source redshift for one system in the new sample of grade A or B lenses.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f1\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f1\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f1_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 1.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 1.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f1_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>\u00a0Grade A lenses. Release 2 of the HSC SSP. Columns 4 and 5 list the lens and source redshift (when measured), respectively. Column 6 lists which subsample of BOSS LRGs the lens galaxy belongs to. Column 7 indicates the grade of the candidate.</p>\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t1_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t1_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s4\" name=\"apjaae381s4\">4.\u00a0Sample Selection for Environment and LOS Analysis</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjaae381s4-1\" name=\"apjaae381s4-1\">4.1.\u00a0Lens Sample</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The sample of lenses used in this study includes the previously discovered candidates from Sonnenfeld et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib66\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib66\">2018</a>) along with new candidates discovered in Data Release 2 (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s3\">3</a>). We only use lenses whose average grades are A or B (definite or probable lenses). To increase our sample size of lenses, we also include previously known lenses in our sample. We search the Master Lens Database<sup xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"fnref\"><a class=\"fnref\" href=\"#apjaae381fn2\">17</a></sup>\n (L. A. Moustakas et al. 2019, in preparation), selecting for systems with a grade of A or B where the lensing object is a galaxy (as opposed to a galaxy group or cluster). The Master Lens Database uses a grading scheme qualitatively similar to our own, and many of the lenses have follow-up <em>HST</em> imaging and/or spectroscopically confirmed source redshifts, so we expect these to be real lenses with high confidence. We add two additional known lenses in the survey area, HSCJ142449\u2212005321 (the \"Eye of Horus\"; Tanaka et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib72\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib72\">2016</a>) and H-ATLAS J090740.0\u2212004200 (\"SDP.9\"; Negrello et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib55\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib55\">2010</a>). We further include two new grade A and B galaxy-scale lenses that have subsequently been discovered by the <span class=\"small-caps\">Chitah</span> algorithm (Chan et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib14\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib14\">2015</a>). These were originally classified as grade C lenses by Sonnenfeld et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib66\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib66\">2018</a>), but were given higher grades by the classifiers in J. H. H. Chan et al. (2019, in preparation).</p><p>We manually remove systems where there is clearly more than one galaxy contributing to the strong lensing (i.e., there are multiple galaxies within the region enclosed by the lensed images). Some lenses outside of the SuGOHI-g sample do not have velocity dispersion measurements from BOSS, while others have measured velocity dispersions smaller than 100 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> or larger than 400 km s<sup>\u22121</sup>, indicative of significant errors in their measurement. We do not include these lenses in our analysis since we cannot build a sample of twin galaxies for them, but we can still calculate their local and LOS environments. Our final lens sample, which we refer to as the \"main sample,\" contains 87\u00a0lenses with a mean lens redshift of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn2.gif\" alt=\"$\\langle {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}\\rangle =0.514$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\langle {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}\\rangle =0.514</script></span></span> and is presented in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t2\">2</a>. For completeness, we show the results for individual lenses not in the main sample in Appendix <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381app1\">A</a>.</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaae381t2\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table 2.</b>\u00a0\nMain Lens Sample\n</p><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\" align=\"center\">1.2255</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.592</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">\u22ef</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\"\u00b1\">296\u00a0\u00b1\u00a063</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">SuGOHI II</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">HSCJ233130+003733</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">352.8770</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.6259</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.552</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">\u22ef</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\"\u00b1\">168\u00a0\u00b1\u00a041</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">SuGOHI II</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">HSCJ233146+013845</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">352.9434</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">1.6460</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.476</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">\u22ef</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\"\u00b1\">188\u00a0\u00b1\u00a062</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">SuGOHI II</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">HSCJ233311+022310</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">353.2963</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">2.3864</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.472</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">\u22ef</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\"\u00b1\">119\u00a0\u00b1\u00a047</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">SuGOHI II</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">HSCJ233528+001355</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">353.8677</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.2322</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.568</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">\u22ef</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"char\" char=\"\u00b1\">230\u00a0\u00b1\u00a043</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">SuGOHI II</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table><p><small>\n<p><strong>Notes.</strong></p>\n<a name=\"apjaae381t2fna\" id=\"apjaae381t2fna\"></a><sup> a</sup>Velocity dispersions from SDSS DR14.\n<a name=\"apjaae381t2fnb\" id=\"apjaae381t2fnb\"></a><sup> b</sup>SuGOHI I\u00a0=\u00a0Sonnenfeld et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib66\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib66\">2018</a>); SuGOHI II\u00a0=\u00a0this work.\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t2_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a>Typeset images: <a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset-multiple typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t2_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">1</a> <a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset-multiple typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t2a_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">2</a> </span></p></div></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s4-2\" name=\"apjaae381s4-2\">4.2.\u00a0Twin Sample</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We construct a sample of \"twin\" galaxies for comparison with the lens sample in a manner similar to that of Treu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>). We select galaxies from the BOSS DR14 using the same selection criteria as for the pre-selected galaxies used as targets for the <span class=\"small-caps\">YattaLens</span> algorithm, excluding the galaxies in the lens sample itself. We then construct the twin sample based on galaxy redshift and velocity dispersion.</p><p>The strong lensing cross section of a galaxy is a steep function of its velocity dispersion (\u221d<em>\u03c3</em><sup>4</sup> for an isothermal mass profile). Given this fact, a lensing-selected sample effectively selects galaxies based on their true velocity dispersion, which could result in an Eddington bias due to which the measured velocity dispersions of our lens sample from BOSS are systematically low. This would result in our selection of the twin sample to select less massive galaxies than the lenses if we did a simple matching based on measured velocity dispersion. The expected velocity dispersion of a galaxy (assuming a singular isothermal sphere profile) is</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn1\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn1.gif\" alt=\"Equation (1)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{SIS}}=c\\sqrt{\\displaystyle \\frac{{\\theta }_{{\\rm{E}}}}{4\\pi }\\displaystyle \\frac{{D}_{{\\rm{S}}}}{{D}_{\\mathrm{LS}}}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t1\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>We can then compare the expected velocity dispersion to the lenses' measured velocity dispersions from BOSS. We have a subsample of 10 lens systems in which we have measured source redshifts and Einstein radii from the literature, and therefore can compare their expected <em>\u03c3</em><sub>SIS</sub> to their measured velocity dispersion from BOSS. Of these 10 systems, 9 have a <em>\u03c3</em><sub>SIS</sub> larger than their measured <em>\u03c3</em> with a mean difference between the two quantities of ~15%. While this subsample is small, it suggests that this bias is real. For the SLACS sample, Bolton et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib10\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib10\">2008</a>) find that <em>\u03c3</em>/<em>\u03c3</em><sub>SIS</sub>\u00a0\u2248\u00a00.948 before correcting for differences in the physical sizes of the SDSS fiber aperture at the lens redshift. This likely has a smaller influence in our sample due to our higher mean lens redshift, and the magnitude of the effect does not seem large enough to explain this bias. Therefore, we must account for this effect when selecting the twin sample.</p><p>For each lens galaxy, we assume the probability distribution of its velocity dispersion is a Gaussian with a mean and scatter given by the value and uncertainty from BOSS. We then weight this distribution by <em>\u03c3</em><sup>4</sup> and renormalize, taking the mean of the new distribution to be the \"corrected\" velocity dispersion. On average, the corrected lens galaxy velocity dispersions are ~13% higher than the measured values. For each lens, we then randomly pick 10 twin galaxies that have a spectroscopic redshift such that \u0394<em>z</em>/(1 + <em>z</em><sub>L</sub>)\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.01 and a velocity dispersion that is within 10% of the lens galaxy's corrected velocity dispersion. We also enforce a condition that half of the twins have a smaller velocity dispersion and half have a larger velocity dispersion than that of their corresponding lens to minimize bias from the slope of the galaxy velocity dispersion function. The same galaxy can be selected more than once if it is a \"twin\" of more than one lens galaxy. Our final twin sample contains 870 galaxies, of which 855 are unique.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s4-3\" name=\"apjaae381s4-3\">4.3.\u00a0Control Fields</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We select random control fields from the HSC SSP by randomly selecting patches (12' <b>&#x00d7;</b> 12' square regions) from the survey patch catalog and then selecting random coordinates within that patch. The chosen locations are taken to be the center of each control field. Patches that have <tt>imag</tt>_<tt>psf</tt>_<tt>depth</tt> &lt;24 are excluded in order to remove fields that do not have a similar depth to the lens fields. We also exclude patches that do not have a defined PSF magnitude depth in the other four filters, indicating that they lack coverage in all five bands. The control sample consists of 100\u00a0random fields that meet these criteria, which is a large enough sample to obtain good statistics within a reasonable computation time. In principle, the randomly chosen control fields can overlap with each other or with the lens and twin fields, but we verify that none of the fields overlap to within a 120'' radius.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s4-4\" name=\"apjaae381s4-4\">4.4.\u00a0Correction for Survey Gaps</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The HSC SSP area has gaps due to survey edges, chip gaps, bright star masks, etc. To account for this, we use the HSC SSP random point catalog (Coupon et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib21\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib21\">2018</a>), which contains randomly sampled points in the survey region that are flagged in the same way as the objects. The random points are drawn with a density of 100 points per arcmin<sup>2</sup>. When evaluating galaxy number counts within our selected apertures, we use the random point catalog to correct the raw counts, <em>N</em>, by a scaling factor to account for occulted area in the aperture. We define the effective number counts as</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn2\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn2.gif\" alt=\"Equation (2)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}\\equiv N\\times \\displaystyle \\frac{100\\pi {r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}^{2}}{{N}_{\\mathrm{rand}}},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t2\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>where <em>r</em><sub>ap</sub> is the radius of the chosen aperture and <em>N</em><sub>rand</sub> is the number of points from the random catalog in the aperture. For small apertures and/or bright magnitude limits where the galaxy density is more sparse, this correction can lead to a bias toward higher <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> in individual fields if most of them do not contain galaxies in the survey gaps (Cooper et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib20\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib20\">2005</a>), but the ensemble of results over the entire sample should be unbiased.</p><p>If <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn3.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{\\mathrm{rand}}/(100\\pi {r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}^{2})\\lt 0.75$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{\\mathrm{rand}}/(100\\pi {r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}^{2})\\lt 0.75</script></span></span>, we exclude that field from the calculation for that particular aperture and lens redshift. Rusu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib61\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib61\">2017</a>) similarly excluded fields from their analysis of the field of the time-delay lens HE 0435\u20131223, testing a cut of both 0.5 and 0.75, and finding that the results were insensitive to the choice of masked fraction threshold.</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s5\" name=\"apjaae381s5\">5.\u00a0Quantifying LOS and Local Environment Overdensity</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjaae381s5-1\" name=\"apjaae381s5-1\">5.1.\u00a0Galaxy Selection</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>To evaluate local and LOS densities, we select galaxies from the HSC SSP catalog that satisfy the following criteria, which are defined in Bosch et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib12\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib12\">2018</a>):</p><ul class=\"clear-list wd-inline-list\"><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">1.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>extendedness</tt>_<tt>value</tt> &gt;0.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">2.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>cmodel</tt>_<tt>mag</tt> \u226424.0.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">3.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>merge</tt>_<tt>peak</tt>_<tt>i</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0True.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">4.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>isprimary</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0True.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">5.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>cmodel</tt>_<tt>flag</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">6.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>edge</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">7.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>bad</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">8.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>saturatedcenter</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">9.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>crcenter</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li></ul><p>\n</p><p>We further require that galaxies lie in patches that have observations in all five bands, even if not to the full survey depth, as the photometric redshifts are less reliable without measurements in all filters. The galaxy magnitudes used in this analysis are cModel magnitudes, which are measured by fitting galaxy models convolved with the point-spread function (PSF) to the light profile of the object (Abazajian et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib1\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib1\">2004</a>). The photometric redshift and <em>i</em>-band magnitude distributions of galaxies selected by these criteria within <em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' of all control fields are shown in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f3\">3</a>.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f3\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f3\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f3_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 3.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 3.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f3_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 3.</strong>\u00a0Distribution of photometric redshift (left panel) and <em>i</em> magnitude (right panel) for galaxies satisfying our selection criteria within <em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' of all control fields.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f3\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f3\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f3\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f3\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>For our calculation of <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub>, we select points from the random point catalog using the following criteria:</p><ul class=\"clear-list wd-inline-list\"><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">1.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>isprimary</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0True.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">2.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>edge</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">3.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>bad</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">4.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>saturatedcenter</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li><li class=\"indices-list\"><div class=\"indices-id\" name=\"\" id=\"\">5.\u00a0\u00a0</div><div class=\"indices-content\"><tt>i</tt>_<tt>pixelflags</tt>_<tt>crcenter</tt>\u00a0=\u00a0False.</div></li></ul><p>\n</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s5-2\" name=\"apjaae381s5-2\">5.2.\u00a0Line of Sight Structure</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We quantify the density of a LOS by the effective galaxy number counts, <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub>, brighter than a limiting <em>i</em>-band magnitude and within a projected radial distance <em>r</em><sub>ap</sub> of each lens. We exclude galaxies that are within 2<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcs.gif\" alt=\"farcs\" align=\"bottom\" />5 of the lens and twin samples to remove any background galaxies strongly affected by magnification bias (e.g., Fassnacht et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>), and exclude a similar region from the centers of the control fields so that we are comparing similar volumes. We test aperture sizes of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn4.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}=\\{30^{\\prime\\prime} ,60^{\\prime\\prime} ,90^{\\prime\\prime} ,120^{\\prime\\prime} \\}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}=\\{30^{\\prime\\prime} ,60^{\\prime\\prime} ,90^{\\prime\\prime} ,120^{\\prime\\prime} \\}</script></span></span> and limiting magnitudes of <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264 {21.0, 22.0, 23.0, 24.0}. Collett et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib18\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib18\">2013</a>) suggest that galaxies projected further than 120'' from a lens galaxy and fainter than <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 are unlikely to make a significant contribution to the external convergence. These limits also encompass the aperture sizes and limiting magnitudes tested by Rusu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib61\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib61\">2017</a>) in evaluating the external convergence in HE 0435\u20131223.</p><p>To separate the contribution of the local lens environment from the LOS, we remove galaxies that are close to the lens in redshift. We define <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn5.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{LOS}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{LOS}}</script></span></span> to be <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> calculated without counting the galaxies that have photometric redshifts such that \u0394<em>z</em>/(1 + <em>z</em><sub>L</sub>)\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.05. The threshold of 0.05 is taken to be a conservative estimate of the typical scatter of the <span class=\"small-caps\">mizuki</span> photometric redshift algorithm out to <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 when applied to HSC SSP data (Tanaka et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib71\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib71\">2018</a>).</p><p>We can calculate the fractional overdensity of a lens LOS relative to a random LOS by normalizing <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> by a factor of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn6.gif\" alt=\"$\\langle {N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\langle {N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle</script></span></span>, which is the mean <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> across all control fields for the same aperture size and limiting magnitude. To ensure that we are comparing equivalent volumes, we exclude a redshift slice of width <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn7.gif\" alt=\"${\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}},\\mathrm{rand}})\\leqslant 0.05$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}},\\mathrm{rand}})\\leqslant 0.05</script></span></span> centered on a randomly drawn lens redshift for each control field when calculating <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn8.gif\" alt=\"$\\langle {N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\langle {N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle</script></span></span>. The uncertainties are taken to be the combination of Poisson error on <em>N</em> and <em>N</em><sub>rand</sub> in the calculation of <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub>, along with the error on the mean of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn9.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}</script></span></span>. This is a conservative estimate, as Poisson error on <em>N</em> dominates the uncertainty budget. For certain applications, it may be useful to have the uncertainties that do not include Poisson error on <em>N</em> (e.g., Rusu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib61\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib61\">2017</a>), so we show these values in Appendix <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381app2\">B</a>. We ignore Poisson uncertainties in the <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> calculations for individual control fields, as they are negligible in comparison to the sample variance.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s5-3\" name=\"apjaae381s5-3\">5.3.\u00a0Local Lens Environment</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>To evaluate the local overdensity in the environment of a lens or twin galaxy, we use a standard measure of environment, \u03a3<sub>10</sub> (e.g., Dressler <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib23\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib23\">1980</a>; Cooper et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib19\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib19\">2006</a>; Treu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>), defined as</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn3\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn3.gif\" alt=\"Equation (3)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}=\\displaystyle \\frac{10}{\\pi {D}_{p,10}^{2}},\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t3\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>where <em>D</em><sub><em>p</em>,10</sub> is the projected distance in megaparsecs to the tenth nearest neighbor that is brighter than <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 and has a redshift within \u0394<em>z</em>/(1 + <em>z</em><sub>L</sub>)\u00a0\u2264\u00a00.05 of the lens redshift. Cooper et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib20\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib20\">2005</a>) find that <em>D</em><sub><em>p</em>,10</sub> is a reasonable estimator of local galaxy environments over a broad range of scales and is reasonably robust to survey edge effects. We correct the \u03a3<sub>10</sub> values for the survey geometry using the random object catalog to calculate a scaling factor as in Equation (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"eqnref\" href=\"#apjaae381eqn2\">2</a>), using <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn10.gif\" alt=\"${r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}\\,=\\,{D}_{p,10}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{r}_{\\mathrm{ap}}\\,=\\,{D}_{p,10}</script></span></span>.</p><p>The absolute \u03a3<sub>10</sub> values depend on the chosen magnitude cut and lens redshift. Therefore in practice, we use a normalized density, <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn11.gif\" alt=\"${{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}/\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}/\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle</script></span></span>, where <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn12.gif\" alt=\"$\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle</script></span></span> is the mean \u03a3<sub>10</sub> evaluated at the center of each of the control fields at the same redshift as the lens being considered. We take the uncertainty on this relative density measure to be the combination of Poisson error on <em>n</em>\u00a0=\u00a010 in the calculation of \u03a3<sub>10</sub> and the error on the mean of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn13.gif\" alt=\"${{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}</script></span></span>, similar to Treu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>).</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s6\" name=\"apjaae381s6\">6.\u00a0Results and Discussion</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjaae381s6-1\" name=\"apjaae381s6-1\">6.1.\u00a0Lens Lines of Sight</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We show normalized histograms of <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> for the lens, twin, and control LOSs in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f4\">4</a>. Each panel represents a different aperture size and magnitude cut. In general, the lens and twin LOSs have higher <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> than the control sample. We quantify the significance of these differences using a two-sample Anderson\u2013Darling test, from which we calculate <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub>, the significance level at which the null hypothesis that the two samples are drawn from the same parent distribution can be rejected (i.e., a lower <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub> means that it is less likely that the null hypothesis is true). Commonly accepted significance levels are <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.05 (2<em>\u03c3</em>) or <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub>\u00a0&lt;\u00a00.003 (3<em>\u03c3</em>). We perform this test in a pairwise manner among the lens, twin, and control samples for each of the aperture sizes and magnitude cuts. These results are shown in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t3\">3</a>.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f4\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f4\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f4_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 4.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 4.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f4_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 4.</strong>\u00a0Scaled histogram of <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> values for the lens (black solid line), twin (blue dotted\u2013dashed line), and control (red dashed line) samples. The columns represent different limiting magnitudes, and the rows represent different aperture radii. The dotted lines of the corresponding color indicate the mean of the distributions. The mean and the standard error on the mean are given for the different samples within each panel. The lens and twin samples have higher <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> in general than the control sample.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f4\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f4\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaae381t3\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table 3.</b>\u00a0\nTwo-sample Anderson\u2013Darling Test Significance Levels\u2014Full LOS\n</p><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>3.0e</strong>\u2212<strong>04</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>6.6e</strong>\u2212<strong>04</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">60</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>1.3e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>1.1e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>8.9e</strong>\u2212<strong>06</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>1.0e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">90</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>3.7e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>2.7e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>7.0e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>1.5e</strong>\u2212<strong>04</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">120</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>1.7e</strong>\u2212<strong>04</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>5.3e</strong>\u2212<strong>04</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>7.4e</strong>\u2212<strong>04</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>1.5e</strong>\u2212<strong>03</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table><p><small>\n<p><strong>Notes.</strong>\u00a0The values represent <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub>, the significance level at which the null hypothesis that the samples are drawn from the same parent distribution can be rejected. Values in italics are significant at greater than the 2<em>\u03c3</em> level, while values in bold are significant at greater than the 3<em>\u03c3</em> level.</p>\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t3_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t3_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div><p>Our results show that the lens and twin samples are consistent with each other and any differences are of marginal significance, as would be expected if lenses are representative of the underlying population of galaxies of similar masses and redshifts. Furthermore, the lens fields (as well as the twin fields) show a distinct difference in their <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> distributions compared to the control fields, with the lens fields skewed toward higher-density LOSs. This is consistent with the results of Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>). The overdensities of each lens's LOS relative to the control sample is given in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t4\">4</a>.</p><div <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a024. Overdensities are normalized by the mean values across all control fields. The uncertainties include Poisson uncertainties in the calculation of lens field quantites and error on the mean in the control fields.</p>\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t4_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a>Typeset images: <a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset-multiple typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t4_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">1</a> <a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset-multiple typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t4a_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">2</a> </span></p></div><p>We then exclude galaxies close to the lens and twin galaxies in redshift space to examine the LOS effects alone. As mentioned in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s5-2\">5.2</a>, we randomly draw a lens redshift from our sample of lens galaxies and exclude objects within a redshift slice centered on that redshift. Using this method we are comparing fair volumes across samples in our calculation. Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f5\">5</a> shows the <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> histograms excluding those within our chosen redshift cuts. Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t5\">5</a> shows the corresponding <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub> values.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f5\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f5\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f5_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 5.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 5.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f5_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 5.</strong>\u00a0As in Figure <a href=\"#apjaae381f4\">4</a>, but with galaxies in the lens plane removed from the lens and twin samples, and an equivalent cut made for the control sample by randomly drawing lens redshifts for each control field. The three samples are now generally consistent, indicating that lenses do not lie along biased LOSs once the local environment has been accounted for. There is still an excess in the lens and twin samples in the smallest <em>r</em><sub>ap</sub> bin. We discuss a possible origin of this effect in Section <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s6-3-3\">6.3.3</a>.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f5\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f5\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f5\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f5\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaae381t5\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table 5.</b>\u00a0\nTwo-sample Anderson\u2013Darling Test Significance Levels\u2014Lens Plane Removed\n</p><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\"
