colspan=\"5\" rowspan=\"1\">\n\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">30</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>2.2e</em>\u2212<em>02</em></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>2.2e</strong>\u2212<strong>03</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>2.2e</strong>\u2212<strong>03</strong></td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><strong>9.6e</strong>\u2212<strong>05</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">60</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">1.2e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">1.2e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">4.0e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">1.5e\u221201</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">90</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">2.5e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">4.9e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">9.0e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">4.7e\u221201</td>\n</tr>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">120</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">3.4e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">1.0e+00</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">7.6e\u221201</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">7.4e\u221201</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table><p><small>\n<p><strong>Note.</strong>\u00a0The values represent <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub>, the significance level at which the null hypothesis that the samples are drawn from the same parent distribution can be rejected. Values in italics are significant at greater than the 2<em>\u03c3</em> level, while values in bold are significant at greater than the 3<em>\u03c3</em> level.</p>\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t5_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t5_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div><p>Once the local environment of the lens galaxies are excluded, they are generally consistent with the control sample, particularly for larger aperture sizes where shot noise has a smaller effect. This result affirms that of Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>), showing that lenses do not lie along biased lines of sight. This is also consistent with the findings of Collett &amp; Cunnington (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib17\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib17\">2016</a>) that show that lensed quasars have external convergence contributions of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn19.gif\" alt=\"${\\kappa }_{\\mathrm{ext}}\\lt 0.01$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{\\kappa }_{\\mathrm{ext}}\\lt 0.01</script></span></span> on average when considering just the projected LOS structure. There does appear to be a slight excess in the lens and twin samples, particularly at small <em>r</em><sub>ap</sub> and/or bright limiting magnitudes where Poisson uncertainty due to small number statistics can be an issue. These excesses are not statistically significant in most of the individual panels of Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f5\">5</a> but appear consistently. We discuss a possible origin of this effect in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s6-3-3\">6.3.3</a>.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s6-2\" name=\"apjaae381s6-2\">6.2.\u00a0Local Lens Environments</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>We compare the distribution of normalized \u03a3<sub>10</sub> values of the lens and twin samples in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f6\">6</a>. The mean <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn20.gif\" alt=\"${{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}/\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}/\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle</script></span></span> for the lens and twin samples relative to the mean of the control fields are 2.68\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.20 and 2.36\u00a0\u00b1\u00a00.07, respectively. This shows that the local environments of both lenses and their twins are more overdense than those of randomly chosen galaxies, as expected. This also suggests a slight enhancement in the local density of lens galaxies compared to twins. A two-sample Anderson\u2013Darling test of the two samples shows a <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.005, which is marginally significant but cannot conclusively rule out lenses not exhibiting a particular bias in their local environment. Treu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>) also find a slightly higher <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn21.gif\" alt=\"${{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}/\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}/\\langle {{\\rm{\\Sigma }}}_{10}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\rangle</script></span></span> for a sample of lower-redshift SLACS lenses compared to their twin sample, but with larger uncertainties and a lower significance. The relative overdensities of each lens are given in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t4\">4</a>.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f6\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f6\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f6_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 6.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 6.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f6_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 6.</strong>\u00a0Normalized histogram of \u03a3<sub>10</sub> distributions for the lens (black solid line) and twin (red dashed line) samples. The mean and standard error of each distribution is given in the upper right corner, along with the <em>P</em><sub>AD</sub> value. The lens galaxies have a slightly higher local overdensity than the twin galaxies, although the significance is marginal.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f6\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f6\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f6\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f6\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>With the longer redshift baseline of the SuGOHI-g sample compared to previous lens samples, we investigate whether the relative overdensity of lens environments shows any trend with redshift. In Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f7\">7</a>, we plot the normalized \u03a3<sub>10</sub> values as a function of lens redshift for the individual systems. There is considerable scatter, but we fit a power law to the points using the methodology of Kelly (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib44\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib44\">2007</a>) to account for intrinsic scatter. We cannot rule out weak evolution, but the slope is still consistent with no redshift evolution in the relation.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f7\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f7\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f7_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 7.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 7.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f7_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 7.</strong>\u00a0Normalized \u03a3<sub>10</sub> distributions for the individual SuGOHI-g lenses (black points) as a function of lens redshift. The black dotted line represents a density equal to that of a random field. For comparison, we plot the SLACS result of Treu et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>) at the mean redshift of their sample (red square), although we note that they use a variable magnitude cut, so their results may not be exactly analogous to ours. The blue line and shaded region represent the best-fit power-law relation and 68% pointwise confidence interval using the methodology of Kelly (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib44\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib44\">2007</a>). We cannot rule out weak evolution, but the slope is still consistent with no redshift evolution in the relation.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f7\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f7\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f7\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f7\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure></div><h3 id=\"apjaae381s6-3\" name=\"apjaae381s6-3\">6.3.\u00a0Possible Sources of Systematic Error</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><h4 id=\"apjaae381s6-3-1\" name=\"apjaae381s6-3-1\">6.3.1.\u00a0Contamination by Stars</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Although the star/galaxy classification should be reliable to <em>i</em>\u00a0~\u00a024 (Aihara et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib3\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib3\">2018a</a>), we check for possible contamination of our galaxy sample by interloping Milky Way stars that may not have been excluded by our extendedness cut. To do this, we plot the mean <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> for a limiting magnitude of <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 within <em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' of each control field as a function of distance from the Galactic equator, <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn22.gif\" alt=\"$| b| $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">| b|</script></span></span>, in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f8\">8</a>. If there is contamination from stars, there should be higher effective number counts at lower Galactic latitude. In fact, there is no such effect, suggesting that our extendedness cut is adequately selecting galaxies.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f8\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f8\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f8_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 8.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 8.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f8_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 8.</strong>\u00a0Mean <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> for a limiting magnitude of <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 within <em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' of each control field as a function of distance from the Galactic equator, <span class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn23.gif\" alt=\"$| b| $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">| b|</script></span></span>. The effective number counts are not systematically higher at low Galactic latitudes, suggesting that our extendedness cut is adequately selecting galaxies.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f8\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f8\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f8\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f8\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure></div><h4 id=\"apjaae381s6-3-2\" name=\"apjaae381s6-3-2\">6.3.2.\u00a0Magnification Bias</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>One might suspect that since lenses reside in locally overdense environments, there may be enhancement or depletion of LOS galaxy number counts due to lensing magnification effects. The direction and size of the effect depends on the logarithmic slope of the cumulative number counts of background galaxies at the limiting magnitude being considered. For a log slope steeper than the lensing-invariant slope of <em>s</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.4, there should be an enhancement, while for a log slope shallower than <em>s</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.4, there should be a depletion (e.g., Chiu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib15\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib15\">2016</a>).</p><p>In Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f9\">9</a>, we plot the cumulative number counts as a function of limiting magnitude for all galaxies within an aperture of <em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' centered on the control fields that have a photometric redshift higher than the mean redshift of the lenses in our sample. We find that the log slope at <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 is <em>s</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.40, which matches the lensing-invariant value, implying that magnification bias is not a significant effect. The slope steepens toward brighter limiting magnitudes, so in principle there could be a slight enhancement in the galaxy number counts at these brighter limits due to magnification effects. However, this will be diluted by lower-redshift galaxies that are either unaffected by magnification from the lens galaxy and its local environment (since they are in the foreground) or have a low lensing efficiency (since <em>D</em><sub>LS</sub>/<em>D</em><sub>S</sub> is small). This effect is also offset by the fact that samples of brighter objects will contain a higher fraction of objects at lower redshift.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f9\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f9\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f9_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 9.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 9.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f9_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 9.</strong>\u00a0Cumulative number counts as a function of limiting magnitude for all galaxies within an aperture of <em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' centered on the control fields that have a photometric redshift higher than the mean redshift of the lens sample, <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2265\u00a00.514. The logarithmic slope of the cumulative number counts at <em>i</em>\u00a0=\u00a024 is <em>s</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.40. This matches the lensing-invariant slope of <em>s</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.4, meaning that any magnification bias arising from overdensities associated with the lens environment should have a minimal effect.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f9\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f9\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f9\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f9\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>We run a simple test to determine how large an effect lensing magnification could have. Using the <span class=\"small-caps\">Gravlens</span> software (Keeton <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib43\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib43\">2001</a>), we generate a mass model consisting of an NFW halo (Navarro et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib54\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib54\">1997</a>) at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.514, which is the mean redshift of our main lens sample. The halo is given a mass of 10<sup>14</sup>\u00a0<em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub>, which would represent a lens environment that is more massive than typically observed, but is still plausible given the velocity dispersion and stellar mass range of our lens sample. The halo concentration parameter for this halo mass is taken from the results of simulations by Zhao et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib82\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib82\">2009</a>), and we assume an ellipticity of <em><img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/epsi.gif\" alt=\"epsilon\" align=\"baseline\" /></em>\u00a0=\u00a00.3. We calculate a source-plane magnification map centered on this model for a source redshift of <em>z</em><sub>S</sub>\u00a0=\u00a01.0, which is close to the mean photometric redshift of the galaxies in the control sample that are at higher redshift than our assumed lens redshift. We then place galaxies from the control sample, which should be unbiased on average, at random locations on the source plane between 2<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcs.gif\" alt=\"farcs\" align=\"bottom\" />5\u00a0\u2264\u00a0<em>r</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a0120'' and calculate their apparent magnitude after being magnified. We compare the number density of galaxies in the unmagnified and magnified cases after accounting for depletion of source area in the fixed aperture due to lensing. We find that even in this aggressive scenario that represents a rich lens environment, the typical effect is a &lt;1% change in number counts at <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a023, with a likely comparable change at <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a024 given the relatively constant slope in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f9\">9</a>. We repeat this test for a 10<sup>15</sup>\u00a0<em>M</em><sub>\u2299</sub> halo, which represents an extreme cluster environment, and find a similarly small enhancement. We therefore conclude that the effect of magnification bias on galaxy number counts is negligible in the context of this study, although we cannot necessarily extend this to deeper surveys or lens samples with a significantly different redshift distribution.</p></div><h4 id=\"apjaae381s6-3-3\" name=\"apjaae381s6-3-3\">6.3.3.\u00a0Effect of Photometric Redshift Outliers</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The photometric redshifts used in our analysis have a scatter and a possibility of catastrophic outliers, as described in Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s2-1\">2.1</a>. Since lenses reside in locally overdense environments, we intuitively expect that redshift outliers will lead to an underestimate of the local overdensity of lens galaxies since more galaxies will scatter out of the lens plane than will scatter into it. To demonstrate this, we show a simple model.</p><p>For a given lens at a redshift <em>z</em><sub>L</sub>, let <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn24.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn25.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}</script></span></span> be the number of objects in the lens plane and along the LOS, respectively, in the lens field. Similarly, let <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn26.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}</script></span></span> and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn27.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}</script></span></span> be the number of objects in the lens plane and along the LOS, respectively, in a control field. The total number counts in the lens field is then <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn28.gif\" alt=\"${N}^{\\mathrm{lens}}={N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}+{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}^{\\mathrm{lens}}={N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}+{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}</script></span></span> and the total number counts in the control field is <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn29.gif\" alt=\"${N}^{\\mathrm{cont}}={N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}+{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}^{\\mathrm{cont}}={N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}+{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}</script></span></span>.</p><p>We then allow for photometric redshift outliers and assume that the global outlier rate applies to both the lens and control fields. Let <em>f</em><sub>in</sub> be the fraction of LOS galaxies that scatter into the lens plane, and <em>f</em><sub>out</sub> be the fraction of galaxies in the lens plane that scatter out of the lens plane and into the LOS. Our intuitive conjecture is that the measured relative overdensity is smaller than the true overdensity. In other words, we expect that</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn4\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn4.gif\" alt=\"Equation (4)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&\\displaystyle \\frac{(1-{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}){N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{in}}{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{(1-{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}){N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{in}}{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}\\lt \\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t4\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>Multiplying through Equation (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"eqnref\" href=\"#apjaae381eqn4\">4</a>) by the denominators of both sides and eliminating common factors, this simplifies to</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn5\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn5.gif\" alt=\"Equation (5)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\lt {N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t5\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>Rearranging to separate the lens field and control field quantities, we get</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn6\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn6.gif\" alt=\"Equation (6)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&\\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}\\lt \\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t6\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>Equation (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"eqnref\" href=\"#apjaae381eqn6\">6</a>) is simply the statement that lenses lie in locally overdense redshift planes relative to a random control field, which our results have already demonstrated. Therefore, our conjecture that photometric redshift outliers will lead to an underestimate of the relative local overdensity of lenses is true, making our results conservative.</p><p>Conversely, this means that there will be a bias in the calculation of <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn30.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{LOS}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{\\mathrm{eff}}^{\\mathrm{LOS}}</script></span></span> such that lens and twin fields will have slightly higher measured values compared to the control sample, i.e., the fact that Equation (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"eqnref\" href=\"#apjaae381eqn4\">4</a>) is true necessarily means that</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn7\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn7.gif\" alt=\"Equation (7)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&\\displaystyle \\frac{(1-{f}_{\\mathrm{in}}){N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{(1-{f}_{\\mathrm{in}}){N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}\\gt \\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t7\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>\n</p><p>To estimate the magnitude of this effect, we first define <em>y</em> to be the true overdensity in the lens plane,</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn8\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn8.gif\" alt=\"Equation (8)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&y\\equiv \\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t8\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>For small <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn31.gif\" alt=\"${\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}}})$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}}})</script></span></span>, we can make the approximation <em>f</em><sub>in</sub>\u00a0\u2248\u00a00 because the total outlier fraction for LOS galaxies is small (of order ~0.1) and the likelihood of an outlier scattering into the lens plane is small (of order <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn32.gif\" alt=\"$\\sim {\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}}})\\sim 0.1$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\sim {\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}}})\\sim 0.1</script></span></span>), so their product is small. We can then define <em>x</em> to be the measured LOS overdensity (the left-hand side of Equation (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"eqnref\" href=\"#apjaae381eqn7\">7</a>)) under this approximation:</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn9\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn9.gif\" alt=\"Equation (9)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&x\\equiv \\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t9\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>\n</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn10\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn10.gif\" alt=\"Equation (10)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&=\\,\\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}+{{yf}}_{\\mathrm{out}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}+{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}.\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t10\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>We can then rearrange Equation (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"eqnref\" href=\"#apjaae381eqn10\">10</a>) to calculate the true LOS overdensity,</p><div xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"display-eqn\" id=\"apjaae381eqn11\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381eqn11.gif\" alt=\"Equation (11)\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\">\\begin{eqnarray}&&\\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{lens}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}=x-{f}_{\\mathrm{out}}\\displaystyle \\frac{{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}{{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}}(y-x).\\end{eqnarray}\n\t\t\t\t\\tag{\n\t\t\t\t11\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t</script></span></div><p>where <em>f</em><sub>out</sub> should be similar to the global value of galaxies that scatter beyond <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn33.gif\" alt=\"${\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}}})=0.05$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{\\rm{\\Delta }}z/(1+{z}_{{\\rm{L}}})=0.05</script></span></span> and, given the typical 1<em>\u03c3</em> redshift scatter, is approximately <em>f</em><sub>out</sub>\u00a0\u2248\u00a00.3, <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn34.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}/{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}/{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}</script></span></span> is the ratio of number counts in the lens plane to number counts in the LOS for the control field and can be estimated from the fractional difference in the distributions for a given magnitude and aperture cut between Figures <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f4\">4</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f5\">5</a>; this roughly gives <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn35.gif\" alt=\"${N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}/{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\approx 0.2$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{N}_{z={z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}/{N}_{z\\ne {z}_{{\\rm{L}}}}^{\\mathrm{cont}}\\approx 0.2</script></span></span>. The factor <em>y</em> can be estimated from Figures <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f4\">4</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f5\">5</a> for a given magnitude and aperture cut and is generally in the range 1.5\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/lesssim.gif\" alt=\"lesssim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a0<em>y</em>\u00a0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/lesssim.gif\" alt=\"lesssim\" align=\"baseline\" />\u00a02, and <em>x</em>\u00a0\u2248\u00a01, thus <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381ieqn36.gif\" alt=\"$0.5\\lesssim (y-x)\\lesssim 1$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">0.5\\lesssim (y-x)\\lesssim 1</script></span></span>. Therefore, the bias due to photometric redshift outliers is a few percent, which may explain the statistically similar but consistently larger LOS overdensities in the lens fields relative to the control fields in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f5\">5</a>.</p></div><h4 id=\"apjaae381s6-3-4\" name=\"apjaae381s6-3-4\">6.3.4.\u00a0Magnitude-dependent Clustering Effects</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Our adoption of a simple magnitude cut may lead to a systematic effect in our calculation of the relative overdensities of the local lens environments. Although our normalization of \u03a3<sub>10</sub> by the average density of the control fields for an equivalent redshift slice should mitigate this, there could still be a second-order effect since galaxy clustering strength is known to be stronger for brighter and more massive galaxies (e.g., Zehavi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib81\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib81\">2005</a>).</p><p>In Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjaae381f10\">10</a>, we plot the relative overdensities of our lens sample against the same quantity calculated using galaxies at <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a023. When calculated with the brighter magnitude limit, most of the relative overdensities remain consistent within the uncertainties, and there is no systematic trend toward higher overdensities. Therefore, there does not appear to be a bias arising from our choice of magnitude cut.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjaae381f10\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381f10\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f10_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 10.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 10.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/867/2/107/Full/apjaae381f10_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 10.</strong>\u00a0Normalized \u03a3<sub>10</sub> distributions for individual SuGOHI-g lenses calculated using galaxies brighter than <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a023 as a function of the same quantity calculated using galaxies brighter than <em>i</em>\u00a0\u2264\u00a024. Most of the normalized \u03a3<sub>10</sub> values remain consistent within the uncertainties, and there is no systematic trend toward higher overdensities. Therefore, there does not appear to be a bias arising from our choice of magnitude cut.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjaae381f10\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadFigure/figure/apjaae381f10\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjaae381f10\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjaae381f10\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure></div></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381s7\" name=\"apjaae381s7\">7.\u00a0Conclusions</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>We have presented newly discovered SuGOHI-g lens candidates from Data Release 2 of the HSC SSP. In total, we find 41 promising new candidates, comprising 7 \"definite\" (grade A) lenses and 34 \"probable\" (grade B) lenses.</p><p>Using these data, along with previously known and discovered lenses in the survey, we have studied LOSs of 87\u00a0strong gravitational lens galaxies to investigate whether they are overdense in comparison to random LOSs in the universe. This study improves on a past analysis by Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>) by taking advantage of the substantial area and multiband nature of the HSC SSP, which allows us to use photometric redshifts to accurately distinguish galaxies in the local lens environment from LOS galaxies in projection. Our results are in agreement with Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>) in that lens galaxies lie in overdense LOS compared to randomly chosen lines of sight, but this effect can be explained by the overdense local environments of lenses. Once the galaxies in the lens plane are removed, the lens LOS overdensities are consistent with the control sample. There may be a magnification bias due to the overdense lens environments, but the effect is likely small and is not strong enough to influence our results. Photometric redshift scatter can lead to a slight overestimate of the lens fields' LOS number counts, but this is likely to be only a few percent.</p><p>We have also investigated the local environments of lens galaxies by comparing them to both a random control sample and a sample of \"twin\" galaxies that are matched in redshift and velocity dispersion. This extends the work of Treu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>) who used the SLACS sample that had a mean lens redshift of <em>z</em><sub>L</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.2, out to a redshift of <em>z</em><sub>L</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.8. We find that lenses have denser local environments than random fields at the same redshift. There is an indication that their environments are slightly more dense than the twin galaxies, although the statistical significance is marginal, in agreement with Treu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>). A bias in the velocity dispersion measurements of the lens galaxies may explain this result, but higher-precision velocity dispersion measurements are needed for confirmation. There is no evidence for redshift evolution in the relative overdensity of lens environments.</p><p>We have calculated the local and LOS relative overdensities for known galaxy-scale lenses in the HSC SSP through Data Release 2. These quantities will be valuable for evaluating the potential effects of external structure and biases that can arise in lens modeling from those effects, as well as for studying the relationship between the environments of lens galaxies and their physical properties as inferred from lens modeling. This work will also inform future studies of this lens sample in terms of follow-up strategies and prioritizing optimal targets.</p></div> <div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>We thank the referee, whose feedback and suggestions were helpful in improving this paper. We thank Jean Coupon for help with the HSC SSP bright star masks and random object catalog. We thank Chris Fassnacht for providing us with his galaxy catalog to directly compare number counts in overlapping fields. The Hyper Suprime-Cam (HSC) collaboration includes the astronomical communities of Japan and Taiwan, and Princeton University. The HSC instrumentation and software were developed by the National Astronomical Observatory of Japan (NAOJ), the Kavli Institute for the Physics and Mathematics of the Universe (Kavli IPMU), the University of Tokyo, the High Energy Accelerator Research Organization (KEK), the Academia Sinica Institute for Astronomy and Astrophysics in Taiwan (ASIAA), and Princeton University. Funding was contributed by the FIRST program from Japanese Cabinet Office, the Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology (MEXT), the Japan Society for the Promotion of Science (JSPS), Japan Science and Technology Agency (JST), the Toray Science Foundation, NAOJ, Kavli IPMU, KEK, ASIAA, and Princeton University. This work is based in part on data collected at the Subaru Telescope and retrieved from the HSC data archive system, which is operated by the Subaru Telescope and Astronomy Data Center at National Astronomical Observatory of Japan. Funding for SDSS-III has been provided by the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, the Participating Institutions, the National Science Foundation, and the U.S. Department of Energy Office of Science. The SDSS-III website is <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"webref\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.sdss3.org/\">http://www.sdss3.org/</a>. SDSS-III is managed by the Astrophysical Research Consortium for the Participating Institutions of the SDSS-III Collaboration including the University of Arizona, the Brazilian Participation Group, Brookhaven National Laboratory, Carnegie Mellon University, University of Florida, the French Participation Group, the German Participation Group, Harvard University, the Instituto de Astrofisica de Canarias, the Michigan State/Notre Dame/JINA Participation Group, Johns Hopkins University, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Max Planck Institute for Astrophysics, Max Planck Institute for Extraterrestrial Physics, New Mexico State University, New York University, Ohio State University, Pennsylvania State University, University of Portsmouth, Princeton University, the Spanish Participation Group, University of Tokyo, University of Utah, Vanderbilt University, University of Virginia, University of Washington, and Yale University. K.C.W. is supported by an EACOA Fellowship awarded by the East Asia Core Observatories Association, which consists of the Academia Sinica Institute of Astronomy and Astrophysics, the National Astronomical Observatory of Japan, the National Astronomical Observatories of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and the Korea Astronomy and Space Science Institute. This work was supported in part by World Premier International Research Center Initiative (WPI Initiative), MEXT, Japan, and JSPS KAKENHI Grant Number JP15H05892, and JP18K03693. S.H.S. thanks the Max Planck Society for support through the Max Planck Research Group.</p></div><h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381app1\" name=\"apjaae381app1\">Appendix A: Lenses Not in the Main Sample and Comparison with Previous Studies</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Some known lenses are not included in our main sample because they either do not have BOSS spectroscopy or do not have reliable velocity dispersion measurements from BOSS (Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjaae381s4-1\">4.1</a>), so we cannot select a sample of twin galaxies for them. There may also be previously known lenses that are contained within the survey area, but that were not in the lens selection function. These lenses are listed in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t6\">6</a>. However, we can still calculate <em>N</em><sub>eff</sub> and the local environment overdensity for these systems. For completeness, we present these results in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t7\">7</a>. Although these systems could have been used in the parts of our analysis that did not make a direct comparison to the twin sample, we exclude them in order to maintain a consistent main sample throughout. Some of these lenses (as well as some lenses in the main sample) may also have independent velocity dispersion measurements, but for consistency, we only use the velocity dispersions from BOSS.</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaae381t6\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table 6.</b>\u00a0\nAdditional Lenses Not in Main Sample\n</p><table cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"0\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjaae381t6\" data-toolbar-img=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t6_lr.gif\" data-toolbar-type=\"table\" data-toolbar-title=\"Table 6\"><colgroup><col align=\"left\"></col><col align=\"left\"></col><col align=\"left\"></col><col align=\"left\"></col><col align=\"left\"></col><col align=\"left\"></col></colgroup><thead>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">Lens</th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>\u03b1</em> (J2000)</th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>\u03b4</em> (J2000)</th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>z</em><sub>L</sub></th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"><em>z</em><sub>S</sub></th>\n<th scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">Reference<sup>a</sup>\n</th>\n</tr>\n</thead><tbody>\n<tr valign=\"top\">\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">SL2SJ021247\u2212055552</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">33.1993</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">\u22125.9312</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">0.750</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\">2.74</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"left\">Sonnenfeld et al. from BOSS or have unreliable velocity dispersion measurements, so they are not included in our main analysis. We list their local and LOS overdensities here for completeness.</p>\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t7_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/aae381\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/867/2/107/suppdata/apjaae381t7_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div><p>We note that two lenses outside of our main sample, SDSS J0924+0219 and SDSS J1226\u22120006, are also in the Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>) sample. Our calculated relative LOS overdensity is consistent with theirs for SDSS J1226\u22120006, but slightly lower than their value (1.20 in a 45'' radius aperture) for SDSS J0924+0219, although their errors are likely large due to their small control sample. The Fassnacht et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib29\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib29\">2011</a>) study goes to a deeper limiting magnitude of <em>m</em><sub>F814W</sub>\u00a0\u2264\u00a024.25 on the Vega magnitude system, which could also affect the number counts (C. Fassnacht 2018, private communication).</p><p>Among our entire sample (including those outside the main sample), there are eight lenses that overlap the Treu et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib73\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib73\">2009</a>) SLACS sample. Our calculated relative local overdensities for six of those systems are consistent with their results within the 1<em>\u03c3</em> uncertainties. Of the two systems where our results do not agree, SDSS J0935\u22120003 is consistent within 2<em>\u03c3</em>, and SDSS J1250\u22120135 is in a dense cluster environment at a low redshift of <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a00.087 where the <span class=\"small-caps\">mizuki</span> photometric redshifts have a higher catastrophic outlier rate (Tanaka et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjaae381bib71\" id=\"fnref-apjaae381bib71\">2018</a>).</p></div><h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjaae381app2\" name=\"apjaae381app2\">Appendix B: Results Without Including Poisson Error on Number Counts</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t4\">4</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t7\">7</a> present the LOS and local overdensities of individual lens systems and their associated uncertainties. Those uncertainties are very conservative since we include Poisson error on the raw counts, <em>N</em>, which are the main contributor to the error budget. However, there may be certain applications of these overdensities where greater precision is desired, so we reproduce those values with uncertainties that do not include Poisson error on <em>N</em> in Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t8\">8</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjaae381t9\">9</a>. We still account for Poisson error in <em>N</em><sub>rand</sub> and the error on the mean of the control sample.</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjaae381t8\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey Department of Astronomy, School of Science, Graduate University for Advanced Studies (SOKENDAI), 2-21-1 Osawa, Mitaka, Tokyo 181-8588, Japan)"], "journal_name": "The Astrophysical Journal", "volume": "867", "publication_year": "2018/11/1", "start_page": "107", "keywords": ["gravitational lensing: strong", "large-scale structure of universe", "Astrophysics - Astrophysics of Galaxies"], "url": "https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2018ApJ...867..107W", "abstract": "We investigate the local and line-of-sight (LOS) overdensities of strong gravitational lens galaxies using wide-area multiband imaging from the Hyper Suprime-Cam Subaru Strategic Program. We present 41 new definite or probable lens candidates discovered in Data Release 2 of the survey. Using a combined sample of 87 galaxy-scale lenses out to a lens redshift of z <SUB>L</SUB> \u223c 0.8, we compare galaxy number counts in LOSs toward known and newly discovered lenses in the survey to those of a control sample consisting of random LOSs. We also compare the local overdensity of lens galaxies to a sample of \u201ctwin\u201d galaxies that have similar redshift and velocity dispersion to test whether lenses lie in different environments from similar nonlens galaxies. We find that lens fields contain higher number counts of galaxies compared to the control fields, but this effect arises from the local environment of the lens. Once galaxies in the lens plane are removed, the lens LOSs are consistent with the control sample. The local environments of the lenses are overdense compared to the control sample, and are slightly overdense compared to those of the twin sample, although the significance is marginal. There is no significant evidence of the evolution of the local overdensity of lens environments with redshift.", "doi": "10.3847/1538-4357/aae381", "custom1": "eprint: arXiv:1809.07341", "issn": "0004-637X", "number": "2"}, "Inspection status": "Complete"}
